    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so with l1, when you say it \"shrinks them down to zero,\" is there a specific reason why it hits zero exactly, whereas l2 just gets really close to zero but never quite gets there? like what's actually happening with the math there?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, indeed. L1 regularization enters the model coefficients directly in its optimization process. The derivative of the L1 penalty with respect to the weights is zero wherever the weights are positive and negative separately (not zero in between), which means it's easier to reach zero values compared to L2 regularization.\n\nMathematically, during the gradient descent iteration in an L1 regression problem, if a coefficient is positive, a small change decreases it, and as our changes accumulate, it easily becomes negative. On the other hand, if it's negative, small changes make the coefficient larger positively, once again enabling it to reach zero.\n\nThe L2 regularization, due to the squared penalty, is always affecting the weights in the same direction because its gradient derivative changes sign depending upon the weight's sign. Thus, it's harder to become zero, as every step of the gradient descent continues pushing the weights in both directions equally.\n\nThis findings from the derivatives of regularization terms, analytically derived, show why L1 might zero out certain coefficients while L2 often keeps them smaller but non-zero.",
      "source": "target",
